      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sparks From a Debate, in New York and Beyond</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard S Lanier letteron Rick Lazio and Hillary Clinton in New York Senate campaign debate; points out that being married to someone who has an affair is hadly the same kind of association, much less guilt, as having served as political cheerleader for Newt Gingrich (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Fierce Opening Debate'' (editorial, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>I was saddened to see you call Representative Rick A. Lazio's reference to ''guilt by association'' in the debate with Hillary Rodham Clinton his ''best line.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Fierce Opening Debate'' (editorial, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>I was saddened to see you call Representative Rick A. Lazio's reference to ''guilt by association'' in the debate with Hillary Rodham Clinton his ''best line.''</p>
        <p>Being married to someone who has had an affair is hardly the same kind of association, much less guilt, as having served as a political cheerleader for Newt Gingrich.</p>
        <p>And to describe Mr. Lazio's flaunting of a soft-money pledge as ''the evening's theatrical coup'' gives undeserved dignity to what was a flagrant violation of the debate's rule, presumably agreed to by both sides, prohibiting the use of props.</p>
        <p>RICHARD S. LANIER  New York, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
